Pilot experiment - Analysis

This file contains the statistical analysis of the experimental data that we collected in our pilot study that replicates the paper “What makes a word special? Words as unmotivated cues” (Lupyian & Edminston, 2015)

First we will have a look at the raw data from the pilot study

# read in data from pilot study
df <- read_csv("pilot_study_results.csv")

# look at the dataset

General information

In total 4 participants took part in our pilot study. We use 6 different categories from which there are each two pictures of category subgroup instances. The average age of the participants is 40.

Data cleaning and transformation

We will remove the practice data. Also we will only consider the trials where the participants response was correct and the categories were matching (auditory cue category fits the category instance shown at the picture).

# remove practice trials
df_main <- df[df$trial_type != 'practice',] 

# rename column info to trial_info
names(df_main)[names(df_main)=="info"] <- "trial_info"

# To estimate which data points have to be excluded we plot a box plot. Now we take the value of the extreme of the upper whisker as maximum value and the extreme of the lower whisker as minimum value. We will remove data points that are above the max_RT and those that are below the min_RT.
box_RT <- boxplot(df_main$RT, data=df_main, ylim = c(0, 5000), plot=TRUE, ylab = "Reaction Time")

min_RT <- box_RT$stats[1]
max_RT <- box_RT$stats[5]

removed <- ((df_main$RT<min_RT) | (df_main$RT>max_RT))
percentage <- sum(removed)/length(df_main$RT)*100
data_clean <- df_main[!removed,]

accuracy <- sum(data_clean$correctness=="correct")/length(data_clean$correctness)

# We use only the trial data where the response was correct and if the categories were matching
data_cor_resp <- data_clean %>% 
  filter(correctness == "correct" & expected =="match")

We removed 44 trials which is 5.73% of the trials from the data because of too low or to high reaction times (outliers). As explained in the preregistration report, we estimate which data points are excluded via a box plot. The minimum value that we accept is the extreme of the lower whisker. The maximum value that we accept is the extreme of the upper whisker.
Here y_min: 440 and y_max: 1737.

Furthermore we only use the trials where the participants gave the correct response, that was the case in 98% of the trials. Now our data set has 724 trials. We will now log-transform the reaction times, because they have a logarithmic distributed shape, rather than a normal distributed shape. In order to make more precise parameter estimation in the regression model used later, the log-transformation is used to get a more normalized distribution.

hist(data_cor_resp$RT, breaks = 20) # this shows us a very skewed data, thus we apply a log transformation

hist(log(data_cor_resp$RT), breaks = 20)

data_cor_resp$RT_log <- log(data_cor_resp$RT)

Overview

Since the pilot study only has a very small number of participants, the data does not represent a distribution of the general population. To get an overview about the pilot data we provide a plot that shows the overall distribution of the reaction time dependent on the trial type (congruent environmental sound, incongruent environmental sound and verbal category label) as well as the standard error that tells us how much the values are deviating from the mean. The jitter plot shows the single data points grouped by the trial type. The data points are color coded for each participant to get an impression of the varying distribution between the subjects. Note that the plotted reaction times are the non-log-transformed reaction time values.

From what we see in the plots it is not clear that the two factors of the experiment (cue_type and sound_type) have an influence on the reaction times. The results of the following analysis will not have enough statistical power to draw a final conclusion. It leads us in a certain direction and helps to test the planned statistical test that we will use for the study.

Preparation for analysis

We use the simple (contrast) coding scheme to dummy code our factors cue_type and sound_type, which each have two levels. First we need to calculate the contrast matrix.

# We need a column that says if the sound was incongruent or congruent to the picture and has an NA in the label trials
data_cor_resp$sound_type <- ifelse(data_cor_resp$cue_type=='label', NA, ifelse(data_cor_resp$trial_info=="congruent", 'congruent', 'incongruent'))

data_cor_resp$cue_type <- as.factor(data_cor_resp$cue_type) 
data_cor_resp$sound_type <- as.factor(data_cor_resp$sound_type) 
contrasts(data_cor_resp$cue_type)
##       sound
## label     0
## sound     1
contrasts(data_cor_resp$sound_type)
##             incongruent
## congruent             0
## incongruent           1

Now we subtract 1/k from the dummy coding contrast matrix that we computed above. k is the number of levels of the factors, which is 2 in our case. For the factor sound_type this gives us the value 0.5 for congruent and -0.5 for incongruent environmental sounds. For the factor cue_type this gives us -0.5 for labels and 0.5 for environmental sounds.

# Prepare data set for analysis

# Applying the dummy coding from above on the two factors sound_type and cue_type
data_cor_resp$sound_type_nr <- ifelse(data_cor_resp$cue_type=='label', NA, ifelse(data_cor_resp$sound_type=="congruent", 0.5, -0.5))
data_cor_resp$cue_type_nr <- ifelse(data_cor_resp$cue_type=='label', -0.5, 0.5)

# We need a column where a unique trial ID is stated, that tells us about what picture/sound exactly it is. This will be included as a random effect in the linear mixed regression model
data_cor_resp$trialID <- paste(substring(data_cor_resp$picture, 18, nchar(data_cor_resp$picture)-4), substring(data_cor_resp$sound, 11, nchar(data_cor_resp$sound)-4), sep=":")

Hypothesis testing

Recall our two hypothesis:
1. Environmental sound cues are not as effective as category labels in activating a concept. That is, reaction times for trials with environmental cues are higher than for trials with verbal labels.
2. Sound cues activate specific category exemplars instead of general categories. That is, reaction times for congruent trials will be lower than for incongruent trials.

In the following analysis we will use linear mixed effects regression models that include our factors of interest as fixed effects (cue_type and sound_type) but also account for random effects, based on recommendations from the paper “Random effects structure for confirmatory hypothesis testing: Keep it maximal” (Barr et. al., 2013). The random effects account for random intercept and random slope effects of within-subject factors, as well as random intercept effects for unique trial types.

# This function is used to compare the complex and the simpler model explained below. The methods used in the analysis we are using are based on and as close as possible to the methods used in the statistical analysis of the original paper.

model_comparison <- function(complex, simple, factor) {
  # First we compute the parameter estimation for the factor of interest
  coeff_complex_model <- summary(complex)$coefficients
  parameter <- coeff_complex_model[factor, 'Estimate']
  std_error <- coeff_complex_model[factor, 'Std. Error']
  
  # Compare the more complex model with the simple model. We compute the chi-square and the p-value that   we use for statistical inference.
  compare_with_simple <- anova(complex, simple)
  chi_sqr <- compare_with_simple['complex', 'Chisq']
  p_value <- compare_with_simple['complex', 'Pr(>Chisq)']
  report_comparison <- sprintf("Estimated parameter = %.2f ,(Std. Error: %.2f), Chi Sqr(1) = %.2f, p = %.4f", parameter, std_error, chi_sqr, p_value)
  
  list(report_comparison, compare_with_simple, parameter, std_error, p_value)
}

Testing the first hypothesis

The first model states that if the cue is a verbal label, it leads to faster reaction times than the environmental sound cues. This would mean that verbal labels are more effective than environmental sounds that are produced by instances of the category. It is compared to the simpler model that does not include the factor cue_type. Remember that the cue_type verbal label is coded as -0.5 and the environmental cue_type is coded as 0.5. The coding of the factors let us make assumptions about the direction of the effect of the cue_type on the verification speed (reaction time). If the estimated parameter (computed from the linear mixed effects regression model) for the factor cue_type is positive, we can infer that trials with environmental sound cues lead to higher reaction times than trials with verbal label cues. Recall that the reaction time values RT are log-transformed.


For hypothesis 1 we fit the model:
RT ~ cue_type_nr + (1+cue_type_nr|submission_id) + (1|trialID)


We compare it with the basic model:
RT ~ 1 + (1|submission_id) + (1|trialID)


Now we investigate if the more complex model that includes the cue_type as a fixed effect fits better than the more simple model, that does not account for an fixed effect of the cue_type (verbal label vs. environmental cue) on the reaction time.

# All the trials that were congruent and the picture was matching auditory label
cuetype <- lmer(RT_log ~ cue_type_nr + (1|submission_id) + (1|trialID), data=data_cor_resp[data_cor_resp$trial_info!='incongruent',])
cuetype.simple <- lmer(RT_log ~ 1 + (1|submission_id) + (1|trialID), data=data_cor_resp[data_cor_resp$trial_info!='incongruent',])
# Using the function above to compare the complex and the simple model
results1 <- model_comparison(cuetype, cuetype.simple, "cue_type_nr")

# Now we would like to compute the confidence intervals to see how precise the parameter estimation is and how much it could vary if we would repeat the measurements. 
confidence_int <- confint(cuetype, method='Wald', level=0.95)["cue_type_nr", ]

Summary of the results of testing for the effects mentioned in hypothesis nr. 1:
- the parameter estimation for the factor cue_type is: B = -0.06, (Std. Error: 0.04) 95% CI [-0.13, 0.02]
- the calculated p-value is: 0.1467718

Testing the second hypothesis

The second model states that if the environmental cue is congruent to the instance of the category subgroup depicted (e.g. hearing a light dog bark followed by the picture of a small dog), leads to faster reaction times than the incongurent environmental sound cues (e.g. hearing a dark dog bark followed by the picture of a small dog). Based on the original paper we hypothesize that sound cues activate specific category exemplars instead of general categories. That is, reaction times for congruent trials will be lower than for incongruent trials.The complex model including the sound_type as factor of interest is compared to the simpler model that does not include the factor sound_type. The sound_type congruent is coded as 0.5 and the incongruent sound_type is coded as -0.5. According to the coding of the factor level congruent and incongruent we can state that congruent sound trials lead to lower reaction times, if the estimated parameter (computed from our more complex linear mixed effects regression model) for the factor sound_type is negative.


For hypothesis 2 we fit the model:
RT ~ sound_type + (1+sound_type | participantID) + (1 | trialID)


We compare it with the simpler model that does not include the factor sound_type
RT ~ 1 + (1| participantID) + (1 | trialID)


Now we investigate if the more complex model that includes the sound_type as a fixed effect fits better than the more simple model, that does not account for an fixed effect of the sound_type (congruent vs incongruent) on the reaction time.

soundtype <- lmer(RT_log ~ sound_type_nr + (1+sound_type_nr|submission_id) + (1|trialID), data=data_cor_resp[data_cor_resp$cue_type == 'sound',])
soundtype.simple <- lmer(RT_log ~ 1 + (1|submission_id) + (1|trialID), data=data_cor_resp[data_cor_resp$cue_type == 'sound',])
# Using the function above to compare the complex and the simple model
results2 <- model_comparison(soundtype, soundtype.simple, "sound_type_nr")

# Now we would like to compute the confidence intervals to see how precise the parameter estimation is and how much it could vary if we would repeat the measurements. 
confidence_int2 <- confint(soundtype, method='Wald', level=0.95)["sound_type_nr", ]

Summary of the results of testing for the effects mentioned in hypothesis nr. 2:
- the parameter estimation for the factor sound_type is: B = -0.05, (Std. Error: 0.05) 95% CI [-0.15, 0.05]
- the calculated p-value is: 0.3364702

The reported p-values are not significant, neither for the first model, nor for the latter. Both more complex models using the factors - cue_type or sound_type respectively - as fixed effect to predict the reaction times does not fit the data better than the simpler model. Also the confidence intervals for both models show that the parameter estimation is not clearly negative or clearly positive.

Since we only have a very small sample size, the results do not let us make a reliable conclusion about the effect of the factors. For more reliable inference we will collect more participants in the follow-up study.

Exploratory analysis

In the exploratory analysis we would like to investigate the more complex models above by performing a bayesian regression approach, using the brms package by Paul Buerkner (2016). It enables us to plot the posterior output of our model and lets us investigate the model more visually and statistically. Furthermore we will compare the estimated parameter for our two factors with compare_groups using the faintr package. We will not compare the two model with each other because they are based on different parts of our data, since we exclude the verbal label trials for testing hypothesis 1 and the incongruent sound trials for hypothesis 2.

# Function to plot the posteriors
plot_posterior <- function(model, data, plot_title) {
  pp_data <- posterior_predict(model, nsamples = 50) 
color_scheme_set("gray" )
plot_dense <- ppc_dens_overlay(y = data, yrep = pp_data) +
  labs(x = "Reaction Time", title = plot_title) +
  theme(title = element_text(size=10))
  plot_dense
}

So now we will first fit the two complex models with brm, that computes a bayesian regression model. Then we will plot the posterior distribution and see how close they are to the underlying distribution.

fit_cue_type <- brm(RT_log ~ cue_type + (1+cue_type|submission_id) + (1|trialID), data_cor_resp[data_cor_resp$trial_info != 'incongruent',], control = list(adapt_delta = 0.99), seed=1001)

The results show: 1. It is very unlikely (14%) that the verbal label cue leads to lower reaction times than the environmental sound cue. 2. It is likely (74,2%) that congruent sounds lead to a lower reaction time than incongruent sounds. Still it is not as likely as expected. A probablity of 95% would be desirable in order to reject the null hypothesis that incongruent and congruent sound cues are equally efficient in order to verify categeories.

Exploratory hypothesis - Categories

When plotting the distribution of the reaction times in congruent sound cue trial dependent on categories we can see that there is a slight variation of performance. In some categories we find the sound more appropriate or more easy to recognize (environmental sound in conjunction with picture of a category) than in others. Here we will only examine the congruent sound trials. If it is true that some categories are more easy to recognize, then it is more difficult to say that environmental sound are motivated cues that always refer to a specific instance. Some sounds could just be harder to identify, which does not necessarily mean that incongruent environmental sounds trials are significantly more difficult to verify as same category.

congruent_trials <- data_cor_resp %>% filter(sound_type=="congruent")
categories_plot <- boxplot(RT ~ cue_category, data=congruent_trials, xlab = "Categories", ylab = "Verification speed (ms)")


congruent_trials$sum_categories <- ifelse(congruent_trials$cue_category=="dog"|congruent_trials$cue_category=="bird", "animal", ifelse(congruent_trials$cue_category=="guitar"|congruent_trials$cue_category=="drum", "instrument", "util_object"))

# Plot the data with the summarised categories (instruments -> guitar and drum, animals -> dog and bird and utility objects -> phone and motor cycle)
sum_categories_plot <- boxplot(RT ~ sum_categories, data=congruent_trials, xlab = "Categories summarized", ylab = "Verification speed (ms)")

We use the bayesian approach to get a more information about the effect of categories on the verification speed in congruent environmental sound trials. We would like to know if there is a systematic effect that yields for all subjects. Explicitly we would like to know if animal sounds lead to faster reaction times than sounds belonging to instruments or utility objects.


Since subjects might be variously familiar with certain categories the model will include a random slope and random intercept effect. The random intercept (by-item) effect is included as well, because we still have unique trial type (like in the models above).


Hence our model looks like this:
RT ~ category_sum + (1+ category_sum | participantID) + (1|trialID)

category_mod <- brm(RT_log ~ sum_categories + (1+sum_categories|submission_id) + (1|trialID), congruent_trials, control = list(adapt_delta = 0.99), seed=2001)
params_cat <- fixef(category_mod)

# Plot the posterior distribution
plot_posterior(category_mod, congruent_trials$RT_log, "Fit of model including summarized categories as predictor")


anim_instr <- compare_groups(category_mod,
               higher = list("sum_categories" = "instrument"),
               lower = list("sum_categories" = "animal"))

anim_util <- compare_groups(category_mod,
               higher = list("sum_categories" = "animal"),
               lower = list("sum_categories" = "util_object"))

util_instr <- compare_groups(category_mod,
               higher = list("sum_categories" = "util_object"),
               lower = list("sum_categories" = "instrument"))

instr_util <- compare_groups(category_mod,
               higher = list("sum_categories" = "util_object"),
               lower = list("sum_categories" = "instrument"))

The model parameters show that the intercept, which is the animal category is higher than the estimators for instrument and utility object categories. To investigate how likely it is that animal categories lead to a lower reaction time, we use compare_groups().


- In 0.9% of the cases the sound of an animal is faster to recognize then the sound of an instrument.
- In 0.11% of the cases the sound of an animal is faster to recognize then the sound of an utility object such as a phone or a motor cycle.
- In 0.5% of the cases the sound of an instrument is faster to recognize then the sound of an utility object such as a phone or a motor cycle.
- The parameters for animal categories is 6.5 with a confidence interval [5.95, 7.04], so it is very likely that there is an effect on verification speed when having animals as category in comparison to instruments and utility objects. The familiarity with pictures and sounds of animals might be the reason, but also that it is more convenient to connect the sound of an animal with a picture of an animal rather than connecting the sound of an instrument or an utility object with its picture.
- The parameter estimation for instrument categories is 0.16, for utility object categories 0.15 and their confidence interval moves around zero, meaning that there is no effect of the two categories on the verification speed.


If we would add more categories to our experimental design this could of course change. Still the result is interesting, because we can say that the lower reaction times for animal categories in congruent sound trials is crucial for the comparison between incongruent and congruent sound trials like we did in hypothesis 1 in the main part of the experiment. Further analysis of the correlation of category and sound type (congruent and incongruent) is conceivable.
